<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="20">
Diagnosis: Distinguished from all other species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A1B16E22-5503-46E3-8E9E-EF7935778506" class="Actinopterygii" family="Pimelodidae" genus="Sorubim" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sorubim Cuvier 1829:293" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="20" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Sorubim</taxonomicName>
by an extremely high gill raker count (31-37, Fig. 1B) and a diffuse lateral-line stripe (Fig. 13).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="20">Etymology: The name maniradii; “mani,” Latin for many or multiple and “radii,” Latin for rakers, in reference to the high number of gill rakers on first pharyngeal arch found in members of this species relative to congeners.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="20">
Distribution: Known primarily from tributaries along the upper Amazon basin (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ríos">Rios</normalizedToken>
Napo, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Marañon">Maranon</normalizedToken>
, Ucayali, Mamore, Madeira, Javari), with at least one specimen collected in the mainstem Amazon near Manaus (Fig. 10). This species probably occurs in Colombian tributaries of the Amazon.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
